<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,151,572]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,224,248]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis box="[199,314,224,248]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
—
</emphasis>
The two species forming the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Dumeril and Bibron" authorityYear="1837" box="[666,733,224,248]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lucius">
<emphasis box="[666,733,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">lucius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group appear at different places on three phylogenetic trees. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Poe, S." box="[151,276,260,284]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="37 - 89" refId="ref41003" refString="Poe, S. (2004) Phylogeny of anoles. Herpetological Monographs, 18, 37 - 89." type="journal article" year="2004">Poe (2004)</bibRefCitation>
they are sister to a clade consisting of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="C. Dumeril and Bibron" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[729,1046,260,284]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Xiphosurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chamaeleonides">
<emphasis box="[729,1046,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Xiphosurus chamaeleonides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cochran" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[1104,1350,260,284]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Deiroptyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="darlingtoni">
<emphasis box="[1104,1350,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Deiroptyx darlingtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In our molecular tree they are sister to all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1826" box="[559,686,296,320]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Xiphosurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[559,686,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Xiphosurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In our combined tree they are sister to all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Daudin" authorityYear="1802" box="[1187,1259,296,320]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1187,1259,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Anolis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1277,1420,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">sensu stricto</emphasis>
). Morphologically, the two taxa in this group appear to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Daudin" authorityYear="1802" box="[1059,1131,332,356]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1059,1131,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Anolis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1148,1290,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">sensu stricto</emphasis>
) particularly in having a T-shaped interclavicle and lacking the many unique morphological features of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="C. Dumeril and Bibron" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[1224,1437,368,392]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Xiphosurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chamaeleonides">
<emphasis box="[1224,1437,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">X. chamaeleonides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Members of that group and all other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1826" box="[761,889,404,428]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Xiphosurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[761,889,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Xiphosurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most importantly differ from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1226,1388,404,428]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argenteolus">
<emphasis box="[1226,1388,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. argenteolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Dumeril and Bibron" authorityYear="1837" box="[151,256,440,464]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lucius">
<emphasis box="[151,256,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. lucius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having arrow-shaped interclavicles. One solution to this non-concordant situation would be to recognize a separate genus for these two species, for which the name 
<taxonomicName authority="Varona, 1985" authorityName="Varona" authorityYear="1985" box="[948,1247,476,500]" class="Reptilia" family="Iguanidae" genus="Gekkoanolis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[948,1088,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gekkoanolis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Varona, L. S." box="[1096,1247,476,500]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="21 - 39" refId="ref42845" refString="Varona, L. S. (1985) Sistematico de iguanidae sensu lato, y de anolinae en Cuba (Reptilia; Sauria). Donana Acta Vertebrata, 12, 21 - 39." type="journal article" year="1985">Varona, 1985</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is available. We eschew that alternative awaiting further study. Only the two species comprising this group, among all dactyloids, have semitransparent scales in the lower eyelid, which separates them most obviously from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cochran" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[1178,1422,548,572]" class="Reptilia" family="Polychrotidae" genus="Deiroptyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="darlingtoni">
<emphasis box="[1178,1422,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Deiroptyx darlingtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
